The founders of Solarex also lost strategic control of their operation. The parent company Amoco had initially allowed them autonomy to continue to cater to small markets, but this changed in the mid-1980s. A new financially oriented management shifted focus and “eliminated everything that was not related to the ‘core business,’” including “the entire consumer business, catalogs, and stores” [(
 
  64
 ), p. 187]. In the 1990s, the division survived through fraudulent tactics used by its partner firm Enron before it was merged into BP Solar (
 
  103
 ).
